A previous study has demonstrated that SALL4 interacts with the nucleosome remodeling deacetylase complex, which contains histone deacetylase 1 and histone deacetylase 2 . In this study, we investigated the expression status of SALL4, histone deacetylase 1, and histone deacetylase 2 and their relationship with phosphatase and tensin homolog deleted on chromosome 10 (PTEN) by immunohistochemical analysis of the posthepatectomy specimens of 135 patients with hepatocellular carcinoma who were treated at our hospital. Ninety-two frozen samples were subjected to quantitative reverse-transcription polymerase chain reaction analysis to detect the messenger RNA levels of PTEN. Seventy-six (56%) of 135 patients were positive for SALL4, and this group had a higher prevalence of hepatitis B antigen, a higher value of alpha-fetoprotein and protein induced by vitamin K absence (PIVKAII) and poor histologic differentiation. High histone deacetylase 1 expression (51%) was correlated with a poor histologic differentiation and a poor prognosis. High histone deacetylase 2 expression (46%) was associated with a higher prevalence of hepatitis B antigen positivity, a poor histologic differentiation and higher prevalence of vascular invasion, and a lower 5-year survival rate. Background: Postmenopausal osteoporosis, a common yet chronic systemic metabolic disease, has become a major public health problem due to life expectancy increasing around the world. The differentiation of mesenchymal stem cells into osteoblasts, and the differentiation of circulating monocyte cells into osteoclasts, play an important role in the balance of bone metabolism. However, when both undergo pathological changes, it can lead to abnormalities, resulting in osteoporosis. This study aims to explore a new biomarker for postmenopausal osteoporosis, thereby providing a new entry point for bioinformatic research into the clinical diagnosis and treatment of the disease. Methods: Using the Gene Expression Omnibus database, microarray analysis was conducted to identify differentially expressed genes in mesenchymal stem cells and monocytes in both postmenopausal osteoporosis patients and a healthy control group. Results: We identified 45 high-expression and 26 low-expression genes through the study, all of which underwent pathway enrichment analysis. This enrichment was observed in the cell cycle regulation, osteoclast differentiation, tumor necrosis factor signaling pathway, and RNA transport. The top 10 hub genes of the protein-protein interaction network were SF3B1, SRSF5, FUBP1, SRSF3, TIA1, KHSRP, LUC7L3, PNN, SRC, and ATRX. Comparing the mesenchymal stem cells and monocytes between the postmenopausal osteoporosis patients and the healthy control group, we noted that the expression of the above genes differed greatly. Conclusions: Through bioinformatic analysis and clinical specimen validation, our study provides a new way for exploring the pathogenesis of postmenopausal osteoporosis. column4: [INST]Context: [PMID: 31136209 Ultrastructural identification of CD9 positive extracellular vesicles released from human embryos and transported through the zona pellucida. However, the secretion of extracellular vesicles from mammalian embryos, especially human, has not been well characterized. Thus, the aim of this study was to 1) identify extracellular vesicles in human preimplantation embryos at different stages of their development using scanning and electron microscopy, and 2) investigate whether extracellular vesicles can cross the zona pellucida and be released from human embryos cultured in vitro. Human oocytes, zygotes, cleavage embryos and blastocysts donated for research were labeled with the tetraspanin EV marker CD9 and analyzed by scanning and transmission electron microscopy. Embryo culture conditioned media collected 3- and 5-days post fertilization were examined for the presence of extracellular vesicles using electron microscopy. We detected numerous CD9 positive vesicles released from all embryos examined. They were observed on the surface of the plasma membrane, within the perivitelline space as well as throughout the zona pellucida. Interestingly, extracellular vesicles were not seen in the zona pellucida of all mature metaphase II oocytes, however, were detected just after fertilization in the zona pellucida of zygotes and embryos. Electron microscopy using negative staining, and nanoparticle tracking analysis of embryo conditioned culture media also showed the presence of vesicles of various sizes, which were round shaped, and had a lipid bilayer. In conclusion, the results of the study provide evidence that human preimplantation embryos at all developmental stages secrete extracellular vesicles into the perivitelline space, which then traverse through the zona pellucida, and are then released into the surrounding culture medium. column4: [INST]Context: [PMID: 27515856 Diagnostic utility of FOSB immunohistochemistry in pseudomyogenic hemangioendothelioma and its histological mimics. BACKGROUND: Pseudomyogenic hemangioendothelioma is an unusual vascular tumor of intermediate malignancy that rarely metastasizes and tends to arise in the lower limbs of young adults and children. Histologically, pseudomyogenic hemangioendothelioma shows fascicular proliferation of eosinophilic spindle cells and/or epithelioid cells showing 'pseudomyogenic' morphology. Immunohistochemically, pseudomyogenic hemangioendothelioma is usually positive for vimentin, cytokeratin, CD31 and ERG. METHOD: We examined FOSB immunohistochemistry in 27 cases consisting of 4 pseudomyogenic hemangioendothelioma and its histologic mimics including 6 epithelioid hemangioendotheliomas, 8 angiosarcomas, 4 Kaposi sarcomas and 5 epithelioid sarcomas . In addition, we performed immunohistochemistry of CAMTA1 which has recently been established as a useful marker of epithelioid hemangioendotheliomas. We elucidated the diagnostic utility of FOSB immunohistochemistry in the differential diagnosis of pseudomyogenic hemangioendothelioma and its histological mimics and also examined the usefulness of FOSB and CAMTA1 immunohistochemistry combination in the differential diagnosis of the tumors. RESULTS: immunohistochemistry revealed diffuse and strong FOSB expression in all pseudomyogenic hemangioendothelioma cases, while the other tumor types demonstrated limited, weak or no FOSB expression. All epithelioid hemangioendotheliomas cases exhibited diffuse and moderate to strong expression of CAMTA1. All tumor types except for epithelioid hemangioendotheliomas showed limited, weak or no CAMTA1 reactivity. CONCLUSIONS: Diffuse and strong FOSB expression was specific for pseudomyogenic hemangioendothelioma in the current series and FOSB immunohistochemistry is an effective tool for differentiating between pseudomyogenic hemangioendothelioma and its histological mimics. Moreover, the combination of FOSB and CAMTA1 immunohistochemistry is useful for distinguishing pseudomyogenic hemangioendothelioma from epithelioid hemangioendotheliomas.] Question: Based on the provided context, do the terms [ERG protein] and [CD31 protein] interact with each other? TRIM37 gene mutations cause mulibrey nanism, a severe growth disorder with prenatal onset. Although TRIM37 depletion normally induces apoptosis, patients with TRIM37 mutations have a high risk of developing tumors, suggesting that there may be an alternative pro-survival mechanism for TRIM37-deficient tumor cells. Epigenetic regulatory proteins support mammalian development, cancer, aging and tissue repair by controlling many cellular processes including stem cell self-renewal, lineage-commitment and senescence in both skeletal and non-skeletal tissues. We review here our knowledge of epigenetic regulatory protein complexes that support the formation of inaccessible heterochromatin and suppress expression of cell and tissue-type specific biomarkers during development. Maintenance and formation of heterochromatin critically depends on epigenetic regulators that recognize histone 3 lysine trimethylation at residues K9 and K27 (respectively, H3K9me3 and H3K27me3), which represent transcriptionally suppressive epigenetic marks. BACKGROUND: Mutations in ANK2-encoded ankyrin-B underlie long QT syndrome type 4 (LQT4) and various other dysrhythmia phenotypes.
